snippet.textDisplay:
babe, i promise you, crying is okay. in fact, it's very healthy to cry. what is unhealthy is keeping emotions pent up until they overflow. as someone who has had depression LITERALLY all their lives (diagnosed with it when I was 7, anxiety when i was 3), i know how it feels to keep emotions pent up, and the effect it creates on my mental health is terrible. if i feel the need to cry, i have to let it out, or i will get worse. so maybe, by crying when you need to instead of waiting every 6 months, your mental health will get better. now, remember, no pity party stuff. dont let yourself go into a downward spiral of pity and depression. that won't help. simply cry to get the pent up emotions out so you can carry on with your life as a healthier and happier person.


(for anyone who might be like "you have no clue what you're talking about," i am quoting a conversation that ive had with my therapist almost word for word, so like, yeah, idk, but therapists are good)

snippet.textDisplay: Saying "I'll be happy when..." prevents us from being happy in the present and places value on the external rather than the internal. Internal peace, untied to the external, lasts longer. I think when we think of happiness we think of it as this constant state of joy and of not ever being sad. The backwards law says that sometimes the expectation for this idealistic happiness can cause us pain. Finding peace within is a difficult task and i hope 2020 can bring us all closer to it 😊
